user.biography: Sharing photos of #Harvard on campus and around the world.

node.accessibility_caption: A person wearing a white lab coat works on a very large computer with gears and wires exposed

node.text:
The Mark I, one of the world’s first programmable computers, was 50 feet long and weighed 5 tons. Designed by Harvard mathematician Howard Aiken in 1937, the enormous computer landed at Harvard in 1944. It recently moved from the Science Center to the new Science and Engineering Complex. Check out our Story to see more.⠀
⠀
#Harvard ⠀
⠀
Photo: @Rosie_Lincoln/Harvard Staff Photographer

Sixteen Harvard students and alumni are competing at the Tokyo Olympics. Check out our Story for more from these Olympians! ⠀
⠀
1. Cheta Emba ’15 – Rugby. Photo: Travis Prior for USA Rugby⠀
2. Umit Gures ’23 – Swimming. Photo courtesy of Umit Gures⠀
3. Gabby Thomas ’19 – Track and Field. Photo: The Ivy League⠀
4. Clark Dean ’22 – Rowing. Photo: USRowing 

#Harvard #Tokyo2020

node.text:
At 140 years old at the time of the American Revolution, Harvard—and members of the Harvard community—played an important role in the country’s early history.⠀
⠀
This engraving by Paul Revere, created about 10 years before the American Revolution, is among the earliest representations of Harvard University, and is part of the Harvard Archives. Learn more about Harvard and the American Revolution in our Story.⠀
⠀
Image: Revere, P., & Chadwick, J. (1767). Westerly View of the Colledges in Cambridge, New England, 1767.
